<CaseStudy slug="competitor-intel-mcp">
  <p class="lead reveal">AI agents can now find and call tools on their own through the Model Context Protocol. That's a new kind of distribution: an agent picks your tool because it works, not because you marketed it. There are roughly 13,000 public MCP servers today and fewer than 5% make any money. I wanted to find out whether a well-built one could.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">What it does</h2>
  <p class="reveal">It exposes a single tool, <code>get_competitor_intel(business_name, location)</code>, that returns a structured report on a local business: its public reputation and any advertising signal. The data comes only from official APIs, so Yelp Fusion, Google Places, and a best-effort Meta Ad Library lookup. Every response includes a <code>_provenance</code> block that states where the data came from and whether it used live keys or a mock fallback. The audience is research and marketing agents running competitor checks and qualifying leads.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Architecture</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The protocol layer and the data clients stay separate. It's written in plain <strong>Python with no dependencies</strong>, so there's no supply chain to worry about and it starts instantly.</p>
  <pre class="reveal"><code>AI agent в”Ђв”ЂMCP/JSON-RPC(stdio)в”Ђв”Ђв–¶ server.py в”Ђв”Ђв–¶ intel.py в”Ђв”Ђв–¶ Yelp Fusion API
                                     в”‚                     в”њв”Ђв–¶ Google Places API
                                     в”‚                     в””в”Ђв–¶ Meta Ad Library API
                                     в””в”Ђ _charge() в”Ђв–¶ Apify pay-per-event billing</code></pre>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>server.py</strong> is the MCP server: JSON-RPC 2.0 over stdio, with <code>initialize</code>, <code>tools/list</code>, <code>tools/call</code>, <code>ping</code>, and the <code>notifications/initialized</code> no-response case.</li>
    <li><strong>intel.py</strong> holds three official-API clients. Each one normalizes to a common shape and falls back gracefully when a key is missing.</li>
    <li><strong>test_local.py</strong> drives the handler with real protocol messages and checks the behavior, so the whole thing is <strong>testable without any API keys</strong>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">A few decisions worth calling out</h2>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Official APIs only.</strong> No scraping, so it stays inside each provider's terms. That's the difference between something you could sell and something that breaks the first time a site changes its markup.</li>
    <li><strong>Mock fallbacks.</strong> It self-tests and demos with no credentials, then switches to live data the moment you add keys.</li>
    <li><strong>Packaged to earn.</strong> It ships as an Apify pay-per-event Actor, with a Dockerfile and an <code>.actor</code> manifest, where the developer keeps 80% of each billed call.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Honest results</h2>
  <p class="reveal">I haven't proven anyone will pay for this yet, and I'm not pretending otherwise. I funded it as a cheap experiment, under $50, with metrics attached. What I can stand behind is the build: a correct, testable MCP server with no dependencies that returns live data once you set keys and is set up to charge per call. The open question is distribution, not the code.</p>
</CaseStudy>
